<h2>SOAP = RPC + XML + HTTP</h2>

<p><font size="4">The above equation summarizes what SOAP is. The
acronym itself stands for &quot;<u>S</u>imple <u>O</u>bject <u>A</u>ccess
<u>P</u>rotocol&quot;.</font></p>

<p><font size="4">It's purpose is to provide a platform
independant way in which for objects to call methods on each
other and thus access each other's functionality.</font></p>

<h2><font size="4">Example of SOAP data packet</font></h2>

<blockquote>
    <pre><font size="4">POST /StockPrice HTTP/1.1
Host: www.stockpriceserver.com
Content-Type: text/xml
Content-Length: <em>nnnn</em>

&lt;StockPriceServerCall&gt;
	&lt;GetStockPrice&gt;
		&lt;Symbol&gt;MSFT&lt;/Symbol&gt;
	&lt;/GetStockPrice&gt;
&lt;/StockPriceServerCall&gt;</font></pre>
</blockquote>

<p><font size="4">As can be inferred from the above example, SOAP
uses HTTP to transmit XML data packets that describe a method
call and any parameters associated with it.</font></p>

